{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}} [[File:Cholera belt.jpg|thumb|upright|1914 advertisement]] A '''cholera belt''' was a flat strip of (usually red) [[flannel]] or knitted wool about six feet long and six inches wide which was twisted around the abdomen before wearing a shirt and purported to be a preventive measure against [[cholera]]. It was a standard army issue and widely believed to protect the wearer from cholera, [[dysentery]] and other ills thought to be brought about by chilling of the abdomen. Their use continued well after the causal agent of cholera was established.<ref name=hist>{{cite journal|title=The history of the flannel binder and cholera belt|author=Renbourn, E.T.|journal=Medical History |volume=1|issue=3| year=1957|pages=211–225|doi=10.1017/S0025727300021281|pmid=13440256|pmc=1034286}}</ref> In 1848 the instructions to army medical officers in India included the suggestion that every soldier should be provided two "cholera belts". In the early 1900s, its use was still recommended for preventing dysentery.<ref name=hist /> In 1914, donations by the tiny village of [[Middlemarch, New Zealand|Middlemarch]], [[New Zealand]] of items such as tobacco, shirts and tinned fruit for soldiers going to fight in [[World War I]], included "26 cholera belts".<ref>Cited on p. 4, Taieri Pet, Newsletter for Middlemarch area, 1 August 1914</ref> The idea of abdominal chilling as a factor in illness was brought up as late as 1947<ref>{{cite journal|title=Acute non-specific diarrhoea and dysentery. Local chilling of the abdomen as a causative factor|author=Kershaw, G.R.|journal=British Medical Journal|year=1947|pages=717–719 |pmc=2053389|volume=1|issue=4507|doi=10.1136/bmj.1.4507.717|pmid=20248097}}</ref> although it was rejoined by those who pointed out that the idea was not based on experimental evidence.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Correspondence. Acute non-specific diarrhoea and dysentery|author=Smith, G.L.Morgan|journal=British Medical Journal|pmc=2055274|volume=2|issue=4517|page=189|doi=10.1136/bmj.2.4517.189-a|pmid=20255535|year=1947}}</ref>
