The '''gay wage gap''' is the pay gap between homosexuals and heterosexuals. Studies have shown that gay men earn less than their heterosexual counterparts, whereas lesbians tend to earn more.
== Phenomenon == An Australian study <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/business/the-economy/the-gay-pay-gap-men-earn-less-but-women-earn-more-20150227-13qmxk.html|title=The gay pay gap: men earn less, but women earn more|last=Wade|first=Matt|date=2015-02-28|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|access-date=2017-08-31|language=en-US}}</ref> has shown, that gay men earn 13% less than their straight counterparts. Meanwhile, lesbians earn 13% more than straight women.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=DANESHVARY|first=NASSER|last2=WADDOUPS|first2=C. JEFFREY|last3=WIMMER|first3=BRADLEY S.|title=Previous Marriage and the Lesbian Wage Premium|url=http://www.readcube.com/articles/10.1111/j.1468-232X.2009.00567.x?r3_referer=wol&tracking_action=preview_click&show_checkout=1&purchase_referrer=bigthink.com&purchase_site_license=LICENSE_DENIED_NO_CUSTOMER|journal=Industrial Relations: A Journal of Economy and Society|language=en|volume=48|issue=3|pages=432–453|doi=10.1111/j.1468-232x.2009.00567.x}}</ref> A study by [[Georgia State University]] from 2009 stated, that queer men earn 8–10% less in government compared to [[heteronormative]] men, even when taking education, race, years of experience and occupation into account.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://splinternews.com/the-gay-pay-gap-gays-get-paid-less-lesbians-earn-more-1793846825|title=The gay pay gap: Gays get paid less, lesbians earn more|last=Rivas|first=Jorge|work=Splinter|access-date=2017-08-31|language=en-US}}</ref> Until recently,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-10-30/tim-cook-speaks-up|title=Tim Cook Speaks Up|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2017-08-31}}</ref> there was no openly gay CEO on the Fortune 1000 list, as the ''[[The Wall Street Journal|Wall Street Journal]]'' investigated in 2012.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10000872396390443295404577547043705374610|title=A Silence Hangs Over Gay CEOs|last=Kwoh|first=Leslie|date=2012-07-25|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2017-08-31|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref> Kirk Snyder, professor at the USC business-school, noted that gay people are better [[Entrepreneurship|entrepreneurs]]. Gay managers have a 25% higher level of employee engagement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://splinternews.com/the-gay-pay-gap-gays-get-paid-less-lesbians-earn-more-1793846825|title=The gay pay gap: Gays get paid less, lesbians earn more|last=Rivas|first=Jorge|work=Splinter|access-date=2017-08-31|language=en-US}}</ref> The National Transgender Discrimination Survey<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grant,|first=Jaime M.|date=|title=Injustice at Every Turn|url=http://www.thetaskforce.org/static_html/downloads/reports/reports/ntds_full.pdf|journal=National Transgender Discrimination Survey|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> reported, that trans people are up to four times as likely to earn less than $10,000 and twice as likely to be unemployed due to [[discrimination]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://splinternews.com/the-gay-pay-gap-gays-get-paid-less-lesbians-earn-more-1793846825|title=The gay pay gap: Gays get paid less, lesbians earn more|last=Rivas|first=Jorge|work=Splinter|access-date=2017-08-31|language=en-US}}</ref> La Nauze, economist at [[University of Melbourne]], noted: "There are grounds for concern that workers in Australia, particularly gay men, are discriminated against because of their sexual orientation."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/document/257191937/Untitled|title=Untitled {{!}} Employment Discrimination {{!}} Homosexuality|website=Scribd|language=en|access-date=2017-08-31}}</ref>
