The '''Haddad''' (also known as the Danoa) are a [[Sahel]]ian [[Muslim]] ethnic group found through [[Nigeria]], [[Chad]] and [[Sudan]], numbering more than 250,000 individuals{{Citation needed|date=November 2007}}. They live in the midst of other peoples and do not have their own language but speak the language of the surrounding community. The traditional employment of the community has always been [[blacksmith]]ry.

They are universally despised by all other ethnic groups, and live segregated, generally without any land or water rights. They are strictly [[Endogamy|endogamous]] and are often considered untouchable by the members of other groups. These sentiments are reciprocated by the Haddad, who maintain a high view of their group. Recently, Haddad members, because of the decline of their monopoly of blacksmithry caused by importation, have started migrating to the Sudanese towns, living beside other ethnic groups.

