ssing of Alumnus Dr. Raymond Paternoster |website=Florida State University College of Criminology and Criminal Justice}}</ref>
==Education== Paternoster received his [[bachelor's degree]] from the [[University of Delaware]] in 1973, his masters' from [[Southern Illinois University]] in 1975, and his Ph.D. from [[Florida State University]] in 1978.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ccjs.umd.edu/sites/ccjs.umd.edu/files/cv/PaternosterVita_0.pdf |title=Raymond Paternoster CV}}</ref>
==Career== Paternoster joined the faculty of the [[University of South Carolina]] as an assistant professor in 1978. He joined the faculty of the University of Maryland in 1982, and became a full professor there in 1990.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.dbknews.com/2017/03/07/umd-professor-ray-paternoster/ |title="One of the smartest people I ever knew": UMD mourns death of professor Ray Paternoster |last=Campisi |first=Jessie |date=2017-03-06 |website=[[The Diamondback]] |access-date=2018-03-06}}</ref>
==Research== Paternoster was known for his research on racial disparities in the application of [[capital punishment in the United States]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/bal-te.md.death06jun06-story.html |title=Court to hear bias challenge against Md. death penalty |last=Goldberg |first=Lisa |website=Baltimore Sun |publication-date=6 June 2005}}</ref><ref name=nyt>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/01/08/us/death-penalty-found-more-likely-if-victim-is-white.html |title=Death Penalty Found More Likely if Victim Is White |last=Liptak |first=Adam |website=The New York Times |publication-date=8 January 2003}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/mar/13/houston-texas-death-row-black-inmates |title=Research exposes racial discrimination in America's death penalty capital |last=Pilkington |first=Ed |website=The Guardian |publication-date=13 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-08-14/news/mn-612_1_black-male |title= 'We Seem Intent . . . on Putting Our Own Apartheid Into Place' |last=Inman |first=William |website=Los Angeles Times |publication-date=14 August 1988}}</ref> This research includes a study of racial bias in [[Maryland]]'s death penalty commissioned by the state's then-governor, [[Parris N. Glendening]]. Paternoster then spent 2 and a half years analyzing data before releasing the study in 2003. The study reported that black defendants who killed whites were much more likely to be sentenced to death than defendants who killed blacks, whether the defendants were black or white.<ref name=nyt/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/news/maryland/bal-md.penalty08jan08-story.html |title=Racial factor found in Md. capital cases |last=Koenig |first=Sarah |website=Baltimore Sun |publication-date=8 January 2003}}</ref> In a 2006 dissent, [[Maryland Court of Appeals]] Chief Judge [[Robert M. Bell]] cited Paternoster's research on this topic as evidence that capital punishment in Maryland was biased against blacks. In his dissent in a case brought by death row inmate [[Vernon Evans, Jr.]], Bell wrote, "The Paternoster study provides substantial evidence that the Baltimore County State's Attorney's Office singled out black defendants from similarly situated white defendants when choosing against whom to seek the death penalty."<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/16295971/ns/politics/t/maryland-court-halts-executions/#.WOO48IgrLb0 |title=Maryland court halts executions |last=Associated Press |website=NBC News |publication-date=20 December 2006}}</ref>
